Consider a library that uses a shared constant for host bindings. e.g.

```ts
export const BASE_BINDINGS= {
  '[class.mat-themed]': '_isThemed',
}

----

@Directive({
  host: {...BASE_BINDINGS, '(click)': '...'}
})
export class Dir1 {}

@Directive({
  host: {...BASE_BINDINGS, '(click)': '...'}
})
export class Dir2 {}
```

Previously when these components were shipped as part of the
library to NPM, consumers were able to consume `Dir1` and `Dir2`.
No errors showed up.

Now with Ivy, when ngcc tries to process the library, an error
will be thrown. The error is stating that the host bindings should
be an object (which they obviously are). This happens because
TypeScript transforms the object spread to individual
`Object.assign` calls (for compatibility).

The partial evaluator used by the `@Directive` annotation handler
is unable to process this expression because there is no
integrated support for `Object.assign`. In View Engine, this was
not a problem because the `metadata.json` files from the library
were used to compute the host bindings.

To fix this, we add support for `Object.assign`. Unfortunately there
is no safe and easy way to detect if a property access resolves to
the `assign` method of the global `Object` variable. To ensure that
the partial evaluator can resolve both the "lhs" and "rhs" of the property
access, we add the needed `Object.assign` types to the ngcc program.

Consider a library that uses a shared constant for host bindings. e.g.

```ts
export const BASE_BINDINGS= {
  '[class.mat-themed]': '_isThemed',
}

----

@Directive({
  host: {...BASE_BINDINGS, '(click)': '...'}
})
export class Dir1 {}

@Directive({
  host: {...BASE_BINDINGS, '(click)': '...'}
})
export class Dir2 {}
```

Previously when these components were shipped as part of the library to NPM, consumers were able to consume `Dir1` and `Dir2`. No errors showed up.

Now with Ivy, when ngcc tries to process the library, an error will be thrown. The error is stating that the host bindings should be an object (which they obviously are). This happens because TypeScript transforms the object spread to individual `Object.assign` calls (for compatibility).

The partial evaluator used by the `@Directive` annotation handler is unable to process this expression because there is no integrated support for `Object.assign`. In View Engine, this was not a problem because the `metadata.json` files from the library were used to compute the host bindings.

### Why should Object.assign work?

Currently ngtsc works with object spread operators. Just ngcc which runs into the transpiled `Object.assign` calls will not support object spreads. This results in inconsistent behavior.

Also, this previously worked in View Engine, so it would help avoiding a breaking change.


### How could it be fixed?

We could add another `BuiltinFn` into the partial evaluator. It will be somewhat difficult to detect whether a expression with `Object.assign` is actually resolving to the default ES6 `Object.assign`.

Since the default libs are disabled in the ngcc program, we cannot simply use the type checker. Joost had the idea of providing these types on our own in the program. That would make the detection easy and also work for ES5 files that rely on the `Object.assign` polyfill.

